09845nam a22013455i 9780823293537DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232935377 a10.1515/97808232935372doi  a(DE-B1597)565981  a(OCoLC)1306541385  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLCO0020002bisacsh00aWild Dreams :bThe Best of Italian Americana /ced. by Carol Bonomo Albright, Joanna Clapps Herman. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (350 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor more than thirty years, the journal Italian Americana has been home to the writers who have sparked an extraordinary literary explosion in Italian-American culture. Across twenty-five volumes, its poets, memoirists, story-tellers, and other voices bridged generations to forge a brilliant body of expressive works that help define an Italian-American imagination. Wild Dreams offers the very best from those pages: sixty-three pieces—fiction, memoir, poetry, story, and interview—that range widely in style and sentiment, tracing the arc of an immigrant culture’s coming of age in America. What stories do Italian Americans tell about themselves? How do some of America’s best writers deal with complicated questions of identity in their art? Organized by provocative themes—Ancestors, The Sacred and the Profane, Love and Anger, Birth and Death, Art and Self—the selections document the evolution of Italian-American literature. From John Fante’s “My Father’s God,” his classic story of religious subversion and memoirs by Dennis Barone and Jerre Mangione to a brace of poets, selected by Dana Gioia and Michael Palma, ranging from John Ciardi, Jay Parini, and Mary Jo Salter to George Guida and Rachel Guido de Vries. There are also stories alive with the Italian folk tradition (Tony Ardizzone and Louisa Ermelino), and others sleekly experimental (Mary Caponegro, Rosalind Palermo Stevenson). Other pieces—including an unforgettable interview with Camille Paglia—are Italian-American takes on the culture at large.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / American / General.2bisacsh1 aAddiego, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAddonizio, Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlbright, Carol Bonomo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aArdizzone, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarbarese, J. T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarone, Dennis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBevilacqua, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonomo Albright, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruno, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaponegro, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarrizo di Camillo, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavalieri, Grace, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCiardi, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCioffari, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCiresi, Rita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClapps Herman, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClapps Herman, Joanna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aClemente, Vince, econtributor.4ctb4https://i